# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ammunition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The **5.56×45mm NATO** (official NATO nomenclature **5.56 NATO**, commonly pronounced "five-five-six") is a rimless bottlenecked centerfire intermediate cartridge family developed in the late 1970s in Belgium by FN Herstal.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] It consists of the SS109, L110, and SS111 cartridges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] On 28 October 1980, under STANAG 4172, it was standardized as the second standard service rifle cartridge for NATO forces as well as many non-NATO countries.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Though they are not identical, the 5.56×45mm NATO cartridge family was derived from the .223 Remington cartridge designed by Remington Arms in the early 1960s, which has a near-identical case.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] However, firing chamber dimensions differ slightly between rifles manufactured for the designated cartridges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The differences may cause unsafe chamber pressures when firing 5.56 NATO in rifles designed for .223 Remington.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Therefore, this combination is not recommended.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In 1954, the larger 7.62×51mm NATO rifle cartridge was selected as the first standard NATO rifle cartridge.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The British had extensive evidence from their own experimentation with intermediate cartridges since 1945, and were on the point of adopting the .280 (7 mm × 43mm) cartridge when the selection of 7.62×51mm (.308) as the NATO standard was made.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The FN company had also been involved in the development of the .280 round, including developing a version of the FN FAL in .280.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The United States overruled concerns about the recoil and overall effectiveness of 7.62 mm, and the other NATO nations accepted that standardization was more important than the selection of a cartridge that was otherwise ideal.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The development of the cartridge that eventually became the .223 Remington (from which 5.56mm NATO would eventually be developed) would be intrinsically linked to the development of a new lightweight combat rifle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The cartridge and rifle were developed as a single unit by Fairchild Industries, Remington Arms, and several engineers working toward a goal set by the U.S.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] A project to create a small-calibre, high-velocity (SCHV) firearm was created.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Eugene Stoner of ArmaLite was invited to scale down the AR-10 (7.62mm) design.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Winchester was also invited to participate.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Springfield Armory's Earle Harvey lengthened the .222 Remington cartridge case to meet the requirements.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] It was then known as the .224 Springfield.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Concurrently with the SCHV project, Springfield Armory was developing a 7.62mm rifle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Harvey was ordered to cease all work on the SCHV to avoid any competition for resources.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Eugene Stoner of Armalite (a division of Fairchild Industries) had been advised to produce a scaled-down version of the 7.62mm AR-10 design.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In May 1957, Stoner gave a live-fire demonstration of the prototype of the AR-15 for General Willard G.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] As a result, CONARC ordered rifles to test.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Stoner and Sierra Bullet's Frank Snow began work on the .222 Remington cartridge.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Using a ballistic calculator, they determined that a 55-grain bullet would have to be fired at 3,300 ft/s (1,006 m/s) to achieve the 500-yard performance necessary.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Robert Hutton (technical editor of *Guns & Ammo* magazine) started development of a powder load to reach the 3,300 ft/s (1,006 m/s) goal.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] He used DuPont IMR4198, IMR3031, and an Olin powder to work up loads.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Testing was done with a Remington 722 rifle with a 22-inch Apex barrel.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] During a public demonstration, the round successfully penetrated the U.S. steel helmet as required.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] But testing showed that chamber pressures were excessively high.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Stoner contacted both Winchester and Remington about increasing the case capacity.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Remington created a larger cartridge called the ".222 Special", which was loaded with DuPont IMR4475 powder.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] During parallel testing of the T44E4 (future M14) and the AR-15 in 1958, the T44E4 experienced 16 failures per 1,000 rounds fired compared to 6.1 for the AR-15.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Due to several different .222-caliber cartridges being developed for the SCHV project, the .222 Special was renamed .223 Remington in 1959.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In May of that year, a report found that five- to seven-man squads armed with AR-15 rifles had higher hit probabilities than 11-man squads armed with M-14 rifles.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] At a 4th of July picnic, Air Force General Curtis LeMay fired an AR-15 and was very impressed with it.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] He ordered a number of them to replace M2 carbines that were in use by the Air Force.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] By November, testing at Aberdeen Proving Ground showed that the AR-15 failure rate had declined to 2.5 failures per 1,000 rounds, resulting in the M-16 being approved for Air Force Trials.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Marksmanship testing in 1961, comparing the M-16 to the M-14, indicated that 43% of M-16 shooters achieved "expert," while only 22% of M-14 shooters did.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] General LeMay subsequently ordered 80,000 rifles.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In the spring of 1962, Remington submitted the specifications of the .223 Remington to the Sporting Arms and Ammunition Manufacturers' Institute (SAAMI).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In July 1962, operational testing ended with a recommendation for adoption of the M-16 rifle chambered in .223 Remington.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In September 1963, the .223 Remington cartridge was officially accepted and named "Cartridge, 5.56mm ball, M193".
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The specification includes a Remington-designed bullet and the use of IMR4475 powder which resulted in a muzzle velocity of 3,250 ft/s (991 m/s) and a chamber pressure of 52,000 psi.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In 1970, NATO members signed an agreement to select a second, smaller caliber cartridge to replace the 7.62×51mm NATO cartridge.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Of the cartridges tendered, the .223 Remington (M193) was the basis for a new design created by FN Herstal.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The FN-created cartridge was named "5.56×45mm NATO" with a military designation of *SS109* in NATO and *M855* in the U.S.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] These new SS109 ball cartridges required a 228 mm (1-in-9 inch) twist rate while adequately stabilizing the longer L110 tracer projectile required an even faster, 178 mm (1-in-7 inch), twist rate.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The Belgian 62 gr SS109 round was chosen for standardization as the second NATO standard rifle cartridge which led to the October 1980 STANAG 4172.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] M1 helmet at 500 yd (457 m) (which was also the requirement for the 7.62×51mm NATO).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] An actual helmet was not used for developmental testing; instead, an SAE 1010 or SAE 1020 mild steel plate was positioned to be struck at exactly 90 degrees.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] It had a slightly lower muzzle velocity but better long-range performance due to higher sectional density and a superior drag coefficient.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The 5.56×45mm NATO has a 1.85 mL (28.5 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 177.8 mm (1 in 7 in), 6 grooves right-hand twist, Ø lands = 5.56 millimetres (0.219 in), Ø grooves = 5.69 millimetres (0.224 in).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] According to STANAG 4172 and the official NATO proofing guidelines, the 5.56×45mm NATO case can handle up to 420.0 MPa (60,916 psi) piezo service pressure.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In NATO-regulated organizations, every rifle cartridge combination has to be proofed at 537.5 MPa (77,958 psi) to certify for service issue.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The NATO military alliance uses a NATO-specific recognized class of procedures to control the safety and quality of firearms ammunition called NATO EPVAT testing.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The civilian organisations C.I.P. and SAAMI use less comprehensive test procedures than NATO.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Over pressure of 25% means 25% in excess of the service pressure resulting from the 5.56×45mm NATO up to 430.0 MPa (62,366 psi) (Pmax) piezo service pressure.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The service pressure is defined as the mean pressure generated by the service cartridge at a temperature of 21 °C (70 °F).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Such a high-pressure proof is conducted with both the weapon and ammunition conditioned to an ambient temperature of 21 °C (70 °F).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Each weapon will be individually tested using an ammunition lot that meets a minimum corrected mean chamber pressure.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The corrected proof pressure requirement (service pressure (Pmax) + 25%) for the 5.56×45mm NATO like the STANAG 4172 is 537.3 MPa (77,929 psi) (PE) piezo pressure.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] This pressure has to be recorded in a NATO-design EPVAT barrel with Kistler 6215 transducer, HPI GP6 Transducer or by equipment to C.I.P. requirements.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The US SAAMI lists maximum average pressure (MAP) for the .223 Remington cartridge as 55,000 psi (379.2 MPa) piezo pressure with deviation of up to 58,000 psi (399.9 MPa).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] When 5.56×45mm NATO was adopted as standard in 1980, NATO chose a 178 mm (1:7) rifling twist rate for the 5.56×45mm NATO chambering to adequately stabilize the relatively long NATO L110/M856 5.56×45mm NATO tracer projectile.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The US at that time converted all rifles in inventory by replacing the barrels and all new US military rifles since have been manufactured with this ratio.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In the US, builders of AR-type rifles can specify barrels with either .223 Remington, .223 Wylde, 223 Noveske, or 5.56×45mm NATO chambers in lengths from pistol (7.5") to long rifle (24").
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] These barrels are also available with rifling ranging from 356 mm (1-in-14") to 178 mm (1-in-7").
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] US makers are moving toward 5.56×45mm NATO and 178 mm (1-in-7"), which will ensure the least liability.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Those chambered for .223 Remington may not have a fast enough rifling to stabilize the longer 5.56×45mm NATO bullets, which range up to 77 gr.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Some hunting loads of .223 Remington go to 90 grains.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The 5.56×45mm NATO SS109/M855 cartridge (NATO: SS109; U.S.: M855) with standard 62 gr. lead core bullets with steel penetrator will penetrate about 38 to 51 cm (15 to 20 in) into soft tissue in ideal circumstances.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] As with all spitzer shaped projectiles, it is prone to yaw in soft tissue.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] However, at impact velocities above roughly 762 m/s (2,500 ft/s), it may yaw and then fragment at the cannelure (the crimping groove around the cylinder of the bullet).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] These fragments can disperse through flesh and bone, inflicting additional internal injuries.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Fragmentation, if and when it occurs, imparts much greater damage to human tissue than bullet dimensions and velocities would suggest.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] This fragmentation effect is highly dependent on velocity and therefore on barrel length: short-barreled carbines generate lower muzzle velocity and therefore lose wounding effectiveness at much shorter ranges than longer-barreled rifles.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Proponents of the hydrostatic shock theory contend that the shockwave from a high-velocity bullet results in wounding effects beyond the tissue directly crushed and torn by the bullet and fragments.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] However, others argue that tissue damage from hydrostatic shock is a myth.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Critics argue that sonic pressure waves do not cause tissue disruption and that temporary cavity formation is the actual cause of tissue disruption mistakenly attributed to sonic pressure waves.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] SS109/M855 NATO ball can penetrate up to 3 mm (0.12 in) of steel at 600 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] According to Nammo, a Finnish-Norwegian ammunition producer, the 5.56×45mm NATO M995 armour piercing cartridge can penetrate up to 12 mm (0.47 in) of RHA steel at 100 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The US Army's Ballistic Research Laboratory measured a ballistic coefficient (G7 BC) of 0.151 and form factor (G7 *i*) of 1.172 for the SS109/M855 ball projectile.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The Swedish military has measured the bullet velocities of SS109/M855 military cartridges at 4 m (13.1 ft) from the muzzle fired from differing barrel lengths.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] There has been much debate about the bullet's allegedly poor on-target performance regarding stopping power, lethality, and range.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Some of this criticism has been used to advocate an intermediate-sized cartridge between the 5.56 and 7.62 NATO sizes while criticisms of poor barrier penetration and accuracy have been used to support the M855A1 EPR round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Arguably, the criticisms about range, accuracy, and lethality are related to the change in barrel length and twist between the M16 and M4.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The earlier 5.56 rounds (the original M193) were optimized for a 20-inch (51 cm) barrel with a 1:12 twist.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In 1980, STANAG 4172 defined the 5.56×45mm NATO chambering and its accompanying 1:7 twist rifling.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The 5.56×45mm NATO standard SS109/M855 cartridge was designed for maximum performance when fired from a 508 mm (20.0 in) long barrel, as was the original 5.56 mm M193 cartridge.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Experiments with longer length barrels up to 610 mm (24.0 in) resulted in no improvement or a decrease in muzzle velocities for the SS109/M855 cartridge.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Unless the gas port can be regulated or adjusted to higher pressures, suppressors for short-barreled 5.56×45mm NATO firearms must be larger and heavier than models for standard-length rifles to function reliably.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] SS109/M855 cartridges fired from barrels under about 254 mm (10.0 in) in length do not have enough muzzle velocity energy to cause extreme damage that occurs only at terminal velocities of over 750 m/s (2,500 ft/s) on impact, reducing the wounding capacity.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The US Army contended in 2003 that the lack of close-range lethality of the 5.56×45mm NATO was more a matter of perception than fact.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] With controlled pairs and good shot placement to the head and chest, the target was usually defeated without issue.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The majority of failures were due to hitting the target in non-vital areas, such as the extremities.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] However, a minority of failures occurred despite multiple chest hits.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Some have contended that shot placement is the most important factor in determining a bullet's lethality.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Difficulty with the 5.56×45mm NATO at long ranges has been attributed to training; Swedish ISAF units relied on .50 BMG heavy machine guns for long-range shooting due to resilience to factors such as range and wind drift.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Underperformance is thus attributed to errors in range and wind estimation, target lead, firing position, and stress under fire, all of which can be resolved through training.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Advances have been made in 5.56 mm ammunition.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The U.S. military had adopted for limited issue a 77-grain (5.0 g) "Match" bullet, type classified as the Mk 262.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The heavy, lightly constructed bullet fragments more violently at short range and also has a longer fragmentation range.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Originally designed for use in the Mk 12 SPR, the ammunition has found favor with special forces units who were seeking a more effective cartridge to fire from their M4A1 carbines.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Commercially available loadings with these heavier (and longer) bullets can be prohibitively expensive, costing much more than military surplus ammunition.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Additionally, these heavy-for-caliber loadings sacrifice some penetrative ability compared to the M855 round (which has a steel penetrator tip).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The performance of 5.56×45mm military ammunition can generally be categorized as almost entirely dependent on velocity to wound effectively.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Heavy OTM bullets enhance soft tissue wounding ability at the expense of hard-target/barrier penetration.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Special Forces had sought to create a round that had increased power out of carbine M4 barrels and compact SCAR-L barrels, while increasing hard target performance.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Developmental efforts led to the creation of the Mk318.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The bullet uses an open-tip design to inflict damage on soft tissue and has a brass rear to penetrate hard targets.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The tip and lead core fragments consistently, even when using short barrels, while the rear moves through once the front impacts.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] It has more consistent performance because it is not yaw-dependent like the M855; the nose fragments upon impact and solid rear penetrator continues to move relatively straight.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] This makes the Mk318 effective against personnel with or without body armor.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The round also increases accuracy, from 3–5 minute of angle (MOA) with the M855 from an M4A1 barrel to 1.71 MOA at 300 yards and 1.67 MOA at 600 yards from a 14 in (360 mm) SCAR-L barrel.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Army adopted the M855A1 round in 2010 to replace the M855.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The primary reason was pressure to use non-lead bullets.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The lead slug is replaced by a copper alloy slug in a reverse-drawn jacket, with a hardened steel penetrator extending beyond the jacket, reducing lead contamination to the environment.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The M855A1 offers several improvements other than being lead-free.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] It is slightly more accurate, has better consistency in its effect on wounding ability, and has increased penetrating capability.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The 62-grain (4.0 g) projectile can better penetrate steel, brick, concrete, and masonry walls, as well as body armor and sheet metal.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] It penetrates 3⁄8 in (9.5 mm) of mild steel at 350 meters, which the M855 can only do at 160 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The propellant burns faster, which decreases the muzzle flash and gives a higher muzzle velocity, an important feature when fired from a short-barreled M4 carbine.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Although the M855A1 is more expensive to produce, its performance is considered to make up for it.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] One possible danger is that it generates much greater pressure in the chamber upon firing, reducing the service life of parts and increasing the risk of catastrophic failure of the weapon (though this has yet to occur).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Marines adopted the Mk318 in early 2010 due to delays with the M855A1.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] This was a temporary measure until the M855A1 was available to them, which occurred in mid-2010, when the Army began receiving the rounds.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Both the Mk318 and M855A1 weigh the same, have similar performance, and outperform the M855 against all targets.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] SOCOM spent less money developing the Mk318, and it is marginally better than the M855A1 in some situations, but costs more per round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The Army spent more developing the M855A1, which performs as well or nearly as well as the Mk318 but is cheaper per round and is lead-free.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] While SOCOM constantly seeks better equipment, the Army and Marines have far more troops to supply and buy more ammunition than SOCOM does.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] If the 5.56 mm bullet is moving too slowly to reliably yaw, expand, or fragment on impact, the wound size and potential to incapacitate a person are greatly reduced.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] There have been numerous attempts to create an intermediate cartridge that addresses the complaints about 5.56 NATO's lack of stopping power, as well as the lack of controllability seen in rifles firing 7.62 NATO in full auto.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Some alternative cartridges, such as the 300 AAC Blackout (7.62×35mm), prioritize penetration and stopping power at short ranges by sacrificing long-range performance.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] These calibers are designed to be interoperable with 5.56 by maintaining similar dimensions, allowing them to be used in a 5.56-chambered rifle with a simple barrel change.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] By late 2004, the 6.8mm Remington SPC (6.8×43mm) was in limited use with U.S.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Special Operators.However, it was not adopted for widespread use due to resistance from officials to changing calibers.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Marine Corps decided not to field weapons chambered in 6.8×43mm due to logistical and cost issues.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Army selected a new rifle and light machine gun as part of the Next Generation Squad Weapon Program.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] They will replace 5.56 mm weapons, being chambered in 6.8×51mm Fury that has greater accuracy and range while being more lethal than 5.56×45mm NATO and 7.62×51mm NATO against emerging threats.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The exterior dimensions of the 5.56mm NATO and .223 Remington cartridges are identical.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] While the cartridges are identical other than powder load, the chamber leade, i.e., the area where the rifling begins, is cut to a sharper angle on some .223 commercial chambers.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Because of this, a cartridge loaded to generate 5.56mm pressures in a 5.56mm chamber may develop pressures that exceed SAAMI limits when fired from a short-leade .223 Remington chamber.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] As the chambers differ, the head space gauges used for the two chamberings differ.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The dimensional specifications of 5.56 NATO and .223 commercial brass cases are identical.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The cases tend to have similar case capacities when measured, with variations chiefly due to brand, not to the 5.56 vs .223 designation.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The result is that there is no such thing as "5.56 brass" or ".223 brass"; the differences between the cartridges lie in pressure ratings and chamber length, not in the shape or thickness of the brass.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In July 2012, the US Army requested vendors to supply alternative cartridge cases to reduce the weight of an M855A1 5.56 mm round by at least 10 percent, as well as for the 7.62 NATO and .50 BMG rounds.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The cartridge cases must meet all performance requirements when fully assembled, be usable by the Lake City Army Ammunition Plant, and be manufactured in quantities totaling approximately 45 million per year.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Polymer-cased ammunition is expected as a likely lightweight case technology.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] A hybrid polymer/metal version of a conventional cartridge case would be thicker than regular cases and reduce the amount of space for the propellant, although certain polymers could be thermodynamically more efficient and not lose energy to the case or chamber when fired.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The pressure limits for .223 Rem and 5.56×45mm NATO are very similar, fired in their respectively designed chambers, if using similar measurement methodologies.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Chamber pressures obtained using different methods are not comparable.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The 5.56mm NATO chamber, known as a NATO or mil-spec chamber, has a longer leade, the distance between the mouth of the cartridge and the point where the rifling engages the bullet.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The .223 Remington chamber, known as the SAAMI chamber, is allowed to have a shorter leade and is only required to be proof tested to the lower SAAMI chamber pressure.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] To address these issues, various proprietary chambers exist, such as the Wylde chamber (Rock River Arms) or the ArmaLite chamber, which are designed to handle both 5.56×45mm NATO and .223 Remington equally well.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The leade of the .223 Remington minimum C.I.P. chamber also differs from the 5.56mm NATO chamber specification.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The casings and chambers for .223 Remington and 5.56×45mm NATO are virtually the same dimensions.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Still, because .223 Remington is designed to handle much lower pressures than 5.56×45mm NATO, the rounds are not completely interchangeable.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Using commercial .223 Remington cartridges in a 5.56mm NATO-chambered rifle should work reliably, but until recently it was believed that it was less accurate than when fired from a .223 Remington-chambered gun due to the longer leade.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Using 5.56×45mm NATO mil-spec cartridges (such as M855) in a .223 Remington-chambered rifle can lead to excessive wear and stress on the rifle and may even be unsafe, and SAAMI recommends against the practice.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The upper receiver (to which the barrel with its chamber is attached) and the lower receiver are entirely separate parts in AR-15 style rifles.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Since all parts are interchangeable, a shooter *must* take great caution to check for markings of 5.56×45mm on the barrel before attempting to fire 5.56×45mm NATO ammunition out of it.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] In more practical terms, as of 2010 most AR-15 parts suppliers engineer their complete upper assemblies (not to be confused with stripped uppers where the barrel is not included) to support both calibers to satisfy market demand and prevent any potential problems.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Some manufacturers have begun offering a hybrid .223 Wylde chamber designed to support both cartridges optimally.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The first confrontations between the 7.62×39mm chambered AK-47 and the 7.62×51mm NATO cartridge M14 rifle came in the early part of the Vietnam War.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Battlefield reports indicated that the M14 was uncontrollable in full-auto and that soldiers could not carry enough ammo to maintain fire superiority over the AK-47.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] A replacement was needed; as a result, the Army was forced to reconsider a 1957 request by General Willard G.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Continental Army Command (CONARC) to develop a .223 caliber (5.56 mm) select-fire rifle weighing 6 lbs (2.7 kg) when loaded with a 20-round magazine.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] This request ultimately led to the development of a scaled-down version of the Armalite AR-10, called the ArmaLite AR-15 rifle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] During testing it was found that a 5- to 7-man team armed with ArmaLite AR-15s had the same firepower as an 11-man team armed with M14s.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Also, soldiers armed with ArmaLite AR-15s could carry nearly three times more ammunition as those armed with M14s (649 rounds vs 220 rounds).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The ArmaLite AR-15, officially designated *Rifle, caliber 5.56 mm, M16*, was later adopted by U.S. infantry forces as the standard-issue rifle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] Hit probability refers to the ability of a soldier to concentrate on firing despite their weapon's recoil and noise, which is noticeably different between the two cartridges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] The 7.62 NATO has twice the impact energy of the 5.56 NATO, preferable if a target is protected by higher-level armor, especially at "medium" range.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] If not, both rounds normally penetrate satisfactorily through enemies up to approximately 600 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] A 5.56 NATO round fired from a 20 in (510 mm) barrel has a flatter trajectory than a 7.62 NATO round fired from a barrel of equal length, while the 5.56 NATO fired from a 14.5 in (370 mm) barrel has the same trajectory as the 7.62 NATO from a 20 in barrel, as well as the same time of flight.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p01] A 7.62 NATO round reaches 50 percent of its velocity within 80 mm (3.1 in) of the barrel when fired, so decreasing the barrel length for close quarters combat results in increased muzzle pressure and greater noise and muzzle flash.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Unless stated otherwise, all ammunition listed below is produced by Thales Australia.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Since 2012, Thales Australia's ammunition production has been conducted via its Australian Munitions subsidiary.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Packaging configurations for all ammunition natures c.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] 2010 consisted of a plastic 8217 box containing 2,700 rounds, divided across nine PVC bags of ten thirty-round cartons each, and a conventional M2A1 box containing 800 rounds, divided across forty twenty-round cartons each.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] For linked ammunition, configurations consisted of a plastic 7716 box containing 2,000 linked rounds, divided among five plastic 7815 cases of two 200-round belts each, and a conventional M2A1 box containing 800 linked rounds, divided among four 200-round belts each.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Unless stated otherwise, all ammunition listed was or is produced by Pretoria Metal Pressings, which became a division of Denel upon the latter's formation in 1992.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In addition to these H83 configurations, blank rounds can come in wire-bound wooden boxes containing 1,000 rounds in twenty-round cartons.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Linked ammunition is supplied in H83 boxes that contain belts of the desired quantity and link configuration (e.g. a 800-round box consisting of belts arranged in a sequence of four ball rounds followed by one tracer round).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Military ammunition was packed exclusively in 20-round cartons from 1963 to 1966.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In late 1966, the 10-round stripper clip and magazine-charging adapter were introduced, and ammunition began being packed in clips in bandoleers.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Typical packaging configurations for M2A1-type ammunition boxes include 840 rounds of ball ammunition in ten-round stripper clips, 1,140 rounds of blank ammunition in cartons, and 800 linked rounds irrespective of ammunition natures.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Typical wire-bound wooden box capacities include 1,680 rounds and 1,600 rounds.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In 1970, NATO decided to standardize a second rifle caliber.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Tests were conducted from 1977 to 1980 using U.S.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] No weapon could be agreed upon, as many were prototypes, but the SS109 was found to be the best round and standardized on 28 October 1980.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The **SS109** was developed in the 1970s for the FN FNC rifle and the FN Minimi machine gun.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] To increase the Minimi's range, the round was designed to penetrate 3.5 mm of steel at 600 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The SS109 had a steel tip and lead rear and was not required to penetrate body armor.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Barrels required at least a 1:9 in rifle twist, but needed a 1:7 in rifle twist to fire tracer ammunition.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The U.S. designated the SS109 cartridge the **M855** and first used it in the M16A2 rifle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The 62-grain (4.0 g) round was heavier than the previous 55-grain (3.6 g) M193.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] While the M855 has better armor-piercing ability, it is less likely to fragment upon hitting a soft target.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] This reduces the transfer of kinetic energy to the target and diminishes wounding capability.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855 is yaw dependent, meaning it depends on the angle at which it hits the target.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] If at a good angle, the round turns as it enters soft tissue, breaking apart and transferring its energy to what it hits.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] If impacting at a bad angle, it could pass through without transferring its full energy.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The SS109 was made to pierce steel helmets at long range from the Minimi, not improve terminal performance on soft tissue from rifles or carbines.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In Iraq, troops that engaged insurgents at less than 150 yards (140 m) found that M855 rounds did not provide enough stopping power.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In addition to not causing lethal effects with two or more rounds, they did not effectively penetrate vehicle windshields, even with many rounds fired at extremely close range.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In Afghanistan, troops found that M855 rounds also suffered at long ranges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Although 5.56 mm rifles have an effective range of 450–600 meters, the M855 bullet's performance falls off sharply beyond 300 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The ranges are even shorter for short-barreled carbines.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Half of small-arms attacks were launched from 300 to 900 meter ranges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] An M855 fired from an M4 carbine has severely degraded performance beyond 150 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The maximum effective point target range of an M4 carbine with M855 rounds is 500 m (547 yd), with a maximum effective area target range of 600 m (656 yd).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] These mark the greatest distances the rounds can be expected to accurately hit the target, not the ranges at which they have terminal effectiveness.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Because the M855 is yaw dependent, it requires instability in flight to deform upon hitting the target.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It is the most stable in flight between 150–350 m (164–383 yd), potentially lessening its effectiveness if it strikes an enemy between those distances.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In addition to this, tests have shown that 5.56 mm bullets fragment most reliably when traveling faster than 2,500 ft/s (760 m/s).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] From full-length 20 in (508 mm) rifle and machine gun barrels, rounds exhibit velocities above 2,500 ft/s (760 m/s) out to 200 m (219 yd).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] An M855 fired from a shorter barreled M4 carbine exhibits a bullet velocity of 2,522 ft/s (769 m/s) at 150 m (164 yd) range.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Even if it impacts at optimum speeds, 70 percent of 5.56 mm bullets will not begin to yaw until 4.7 in (120 mm) of tissue penetration.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] 15 percent more begin to yaw after that distance, so up to 85 percent of rounds that hit do not start to fragment until nearly 5 in of penetration.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Against small-statured or thin combatants, the M855 has little chance of yawing before passing through cleanly and leaving a wound cavity no bigger than the bullet itself.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The factors of impact angle and velocity, instability distance, and penetration before yaw reduce the round's predictable effectiveness considerably in combat situations.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The **M855A1 Enhanced Performance Round** (EPR) was introduced in June 2010.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It features a lead-free 62-grain (4.0 g) projectile with a solid copper core, and is tailored for use in rifles with shorter barrels such as the M4 carbine.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It provides more consistent performance compared to the M855.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] On 24 June 2010, the United States Army announced that it had begun shipping its new 5.56 mm cartridge, the **M855A1 Enhanced Performance Round** (EPR), to active combat zones.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] During testing, the M855A1 performed better than M80 7.62×51mm NATO ball ammunition against certain types of targets (particularly hardened steel).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] However, this was due to the addition of a steel penetrator to the M855A1 projectile, compared to the standard lead-alloy core of the M80 projectile, and is not an accurate comparison between the two cartridges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The US Army Picatinny Arsenal stated that the new M855A1 offers improved hard-target capability, more consistent performance at all distances, enhanced reliability, improved accuracy, reduced muzzle flash, and higher velocity than the SS109/M855 round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Further, the Army stated that the new M855A1 ammunition is tailored for use in M4 carbines but should also deliver enhanced performance in M16 rifles and M249 light machine guns.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The new 62-grain (4.0 g)-grain projectile used in the M855A1 round has a copper core with a 19-grain (1.2 g)-grain steel "stacked-cone" penetrating tip.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855A1 cartridge is sometimes referred to as "green ammo" because it fires a lead free projectile.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It is not necessarily more lethal than the SS109/M855, but performs more consistently every time it hits a soft target and retains its performance at longer distances.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The EPR can penetrate a 3⁄8 in (9.5 mm) thick mild steel barrier from an M4 at 350 m (380 yd) and from an M16 at 400 m (440 yd).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Ballistics for both rounds are similar and do not require weapons to be re-zeroed, but if they are the EPR can be slightly more accurate.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The steel-tip penetrator of the M855A1 is noticeably separated from the bullet jacket and can spin, but this is part of the design and does not affect performance.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855A1 costs only 5 cents more per round than the M855.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855A1 bullet has a 1⁄8 in (3.2 mm) greater length than the SS109/M855.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Because steel and copper are less dense than lead, the bullet is lengthened inside the case to achieve the same weight as its predecessor.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The longer bullet and reverse-drawn jacket make it more stable and accurate in-flight.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Its steel tip is exposed from the jacket and bronzed for corrosion resistance.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The tip is serrated and larger than the M855's steel tip.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855A1's bullet composition, improved aerodynamics, and higher proof pressures extend its effective range for penetration and terminal performance.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] While effectiveness at different ranges is increased, the M855A1 does not increase the effective ranges at which weapons are expected to hit their targets.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Enhanced Performance Round was made to nearly match the trajectory of the M855 to aid in training consistency—the SS109/M855 ballistic coefficient (G7 BC) of 0.151 was improved to 0.152 for the M855A1—but the ranges to get desired effects are greatly extended.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The United States Marine Corps purchased 1.8 million rounds in 2010, with plans to adopt the round to replace the interim MK318 SOST rounds used in Afghanistan when the M855A1 project was delayed.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Marine Corps plans to adopt the M855A1 round in 2018; although testing revealed it caused "some durability issues" with the Marines' M27 Infantry Automatic Rifle, the weapon is still "operationally suitable" when firing the round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] On a media day at Aberdeen Proving Ground on 4 May 2011, reports were given about the M855A1's performance in the field since it was issued 11 months earlier.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] One primary advantage given by the round is its consistent performance against soft targets.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] While the older SS109/M855 was yaw-dependent, which means its effectiveness depends on its yaw angle when it hits a target, the M855A1 delivers the same effectiveness in a soft target, no matter its yaw angle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The new SMP-842 propellant in the round burns quicker in the shorter M4 carbine barrel, ensuring less muzzle flash and greater muzzle velocity.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855A1 was able to penetrate 3⁄8 inch (9.5 mm) of mild steel plate at 300 m (330 yd).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The round even penetrated concrete masonry units, similar to cinder blocks, at 75 m (82 yd) from an M16 and at 50 m (55 yd) from an M4, which the M855 could not do at those ranges.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Its accuracy is maintained and sometimes increased, as it was able to shoot a group 2 inches (51 mm) better at 600 m (660 yd).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In February 2011, the M855A1 was used more than the M855, and approximately 30 million M855A1 rounds were fielded from June 2010 to May 2011.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The M855A1 was put to the test at the 2012 National Rifle Association's National High-Power Rifle Championship at Camp Perry, Ohio, in August 2012.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The shooter for the Army was Rob Harbison, a contractor supporting small caliber ammunition capability development at Fort Benning Georgia.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] This was a special event for the Project Manager for Maneuver Ammunition Systems and the Army's Maneuver Center of Excellence, as it was an opportunity to showcase the Enhanced Performance Round's capabilities.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] With an M16 loaded with M855A1 ammo, Harbison fired a perfect 200 points in the Coast Guard Trophy Match, which is 20 shots fired from the sitting position at 200 yards, finishing 17th out of 365 competitors.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] He also scored a perfect 100 on the final string of ten shots during the Air Force Cup Trophy Match, fired at 600 yards from the prone position, which is 10 shots in a row within the 12-inch, 10-point ring at 600 yards with combat ammunition.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Harbison was happy with the EPR's performance, with his scores showing that the Army's newest general-purpose round is accurate enough to go toe-to-toe with the best ammo available, whether bought or hand-loaded.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] From fielding in June 2010 to September 2012, Alliant Techsystems delivered over 350 million M855A1 Enhanced Performance Rounds.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Since its introduction, the M855A1 has been criticized for its St.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Mark's SMP842 (former WC842) ball propellant, which has been shown to increase fouling of the gun barrel.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Post-combat surveys have reported no issues with the EPR in combat.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] A series of tests found no significant difference in fouling between the old M855 and the M855A1.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] However, manufacturers have reported "severe degradation" of barrels in rifles using the M855A1 in tests.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Army attributes pressure and wear issues with the M855A1 to problems with the primer, which they claim to have addressed with a newly designed primer.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It uses a modified four-pronged primer anvil for more reliable powder ignition, with a stab crimp rather than a circumferential crimp to better withstand the new load's higher chamber pressure, increased from 55,000 psi (379.2 MPa) to 62,000 psi (427.5 MPa).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] During Army carbine testing, the round caused "accelerated bolt wear" from higher chamber pressure and increased bore temperatures.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Special Operator testing saw cracks appear on locking lugs and bolts at cam pin holes on average at 6,000 rounds, but sometimes as few as 3,000 rounds during intense automatic firing.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Firing several thousand rounds at such high chamber pressures can degrade accuracy over time as parts wear out; these effects can be mitigated by using a round counter to track part service life.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Weapons with barrel lengths shorter than the M4 firing the M855A1 also experience 50 percent higher pressures than a full-length M16 rifle barrel, which can cause port erosion that can boost the automatic fire rate, increasing the likelihood of jams.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] From June 2010 to June 2013, the issuing of the M855A1 Enhanced Performance Round removed 1,994 metric tons of lead from the waste stream.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] 2.1 grams (32 gr) of lead are eliminated from each M855A1 projectile.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The **Mk 262** is a match-quality round manufactured by Black Hills Ammunition made originally for the Special Purpose Rifle (SPR).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It uses a 77-grain (5.0 g) Sierra MatchKing bullet that is more effective at longer ranges than the standard issue M855 round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In 1999, SOCOM requested Black Hills Ammunition to develop ammunition for the Mk 12 SPR that SOCOM was designing.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Issues came up in development, including reliability problems at different temperatures and when the weapon got dirty, and cycling issues in cold weather due to the slightly shorter SPR barrel compared to the full-length M16A2 barrel.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The problems were addressed by using a slower-burning powder with a different pressure in the barrel, resulting in the Mk 262 MOD 1 in 2003.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] During the product improvement stage, the new propellant was found to be more heat-sensitive in weapon chambers during rapid firings, resulting in higher pressures and failure to extract.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] This was addressed with another powder blend with higher heat tolerance and improved brass.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Also during the stage, Black Hills wanted the bullet to be given a cannelure, which had been previously rejected for fear it would affect accuracy.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It was eventually added to ensure effective crimping and prevent the projectile from moving back into the case, causing a malfunction during auto-load feeding.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Although the temperature-sensitive powder and new bullet changed specifications, the designation remained as the MOD 1.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] According to US DoD sources, the Mk 262 round is capable of making kills at 700 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Ballistics tests found that the round caused "consistent initial yaw in soft tissue" between 3 and 4 inches at ranges from 15 feet to 300 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Apparently, it is superior to the standard M855 round when fired from an M4 or M16 rifle, increasing accuracy from 3–5 minutes of angle to 2 minutes of angle.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It possesses superior stopping power and can extend engagements to up to 700 meters when fired from an 18-inch barrel.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It appears that this round can drastically improve the performance of any AR-15 weapon chambered to .223/5.56 mm.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Superior accuracy, wounding capacity, stopping power, and range have made this the preferred round of many special forces operators and a highly desirable replacement for the older, Belgian-designed 5.56×45mm SS109/M855 NATO round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In one engagement, a two-man special forces team reported 75 kills with 77 rounds.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Mk 262 has a higher ballistic coefficient than the M855 of (G1)0.362 / (G7)0.181, meaning it loses less velocity at long-range.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Black Hills also produces the MK262 Mod-1C for sale in the US civilian market under Product Code D556N9.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Following early engagements in Afghanistan and Iraq, U.S.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Special Operations Forces reported that M855 ammunition used in M4A1 rifles was ineffective.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In 2005, the Pentagon issued a formal request to the ammunition industry for "enhanced" ammunition.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The only business that responded was the Federal Cartridge Company, owned by Alliant Techsystems.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The prototypes were delivered to the government in August 2007.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Increased velocity and decreased muzzle flash were accomplished by the type of powder used.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The bullet's design was called the Open Tip Match Rear Penetrator (OTMRP).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The front is an open tip backed by a lead core, while the rear half is solid brass.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] When the bullet hits a hard barrier, the front half of the bullet crushes against the barrier, breaking it so the penetrating half of the bullet can go through and hit the target.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] With the lead section penetrating the target and the brass section following, it was referred to as a "barrier blind" bullet.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Officially designated the **MK 318 MOD 0 "Cartridge, Caliber 5.56mm Ball, Carbine, Barrier"**, and called *SOST (Special Operations Science and Technology)* ammunition, the 62-grain (4.0 g) bullet fragments consistently, even out of a 10.5 in barrel.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The lead portion fragments in the first few inches of soft tissue, then the solid copper rear penetrates 18 in of tissue (as shown through ballistic gelatin) while tumbling.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Out of a 14 in barrel, the Mk 318 has a muzzle velocity of 2,925 ft/s (892 m/s).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Marine Corps adopted the Mk 318 for infantry use.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] To be fielded by an entire branch of the military, the round is classified as having an "open-tip" bullet, similar to the M118LR 7.62 NATO round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The SOST bullet uses a "reverse drawn" forming process.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The base of the bullet is made first, the lead core is placed on top of it, and then the jacketing is pulled up around the lead core from bottom to tip.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Conventional, and cheaper, bullets are made by drawing the jacket from the nose to an exposed lead base.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The reverse-drawn technique leaves an open tip as a byproduct of the manufacturing process and is not specifically designed for expansion or to affect terminal ballistics.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Pentagon legally cleared the rounds for Marine use in late January.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Marines fielded the Mk318 gradually and in small numbers.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Initial studies showed that insurgents hit by it suffered larger exit wounds, although information was limited.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] SOST rounds were used alongside M855 rounds in situations where the SOST would be more effective.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In July 2010, the Marines purchased 1.8 million M855A1 Enhanced Performance Rounds, in addition to millions of Mk318 rounds in service, as part of its effort to replace its M855 ammo.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] As of May 2015, Marine combat units still deployed with a mixture of both SOST and M855 rounds.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] As the issue of environmentally friendly ammo grew, the Marines sought to determine whether the Mk 318's lead could be replaced while still meeting specifications.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] They found that by replacing the lead with copper and slightly stretching the jacket around to crimp the nose even more, the bullet's ballistic coefficient increased.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] To avoid visual confusion with the Mk 262 round, the bullet was entirely nickel-plated for a silver color; the enhanced silver-colored copper jacketed, open tip match, 62-grain projectile was named the **MK 318 MOD 1**.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The **5.6mm *Gewehr Patrone* 90** or **5,6mm Gw Pat 90** (5.6 mm Rifle Cartridge 90), is the standard round used by the Swiss military in its rifle, the SIG SG 550.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The cartridge is also known as the **Cart 5,6mm 90 F** (French: *Cartouche pour Fusil* / Italian: *Cartuccia per Fucile*) to the French- and Italian-speaking Swiss militiamen.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Swiss refer to the round as the 5.6 mm Gw Pat 90, although it is interchangeable with the 5.56×45mm NATO and .223 Remington round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Gw Pat 90 round firing a 4.1-gram (63 gr) FMJ bullet is optimized for use in 5.56 mm (.223 in) caliber barrels with a 254 mm (1:10 in) twist rate.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Gw Pat 90 was designed for the SIG SG 550 when it came into production in 1987, replacing the SIG SG 510.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Previous experience with a change in standard rifle had proved that changing the firing distance for the training ranges was more expensive than designing a new ammunition; this prompted the design of a cartridge nominally capable of 300 meters.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The cartridge was also designed to reduce pollution by controlling lead emissions.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The bullet was originally clad with a nickel alloy jacket; however, this was found to cause excessive barrel wear, so in 1998 the nickel jackets were replaced with tombac jackets.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] In addition, in 1999, a copper plug was added to the base of the bullet to address environmental concerns.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] As of 2009 the ammunition was produced by RUAG Ammotec, a subsidiary of the RUAG group.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] It is manufactured in three variations: the standard FMJ round, the tracer round, and a blank round.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The FMJ cartridge has a copper-zinc alloy case and uses a double-base propellant.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The bullet is a 4.1-gram (63 gr) tombac jacketed FMJ projectile with a G1 ballistic coefficient of 0.331 (ICAO) / 0.337 (Army Metro).
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The projectile contains approximately 95% lead, 2% tin, 3% copper and was designed for terminal ballistic instability.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The required accuracy for Gw Pat 90 ammunition out of factory test barrels is 63 mm (0.72 MOA) for 10 rounds (100% radius measurement method) out to 300 m.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Gw Pat 90 cartridge dimensions are in accordance with the civilian C.I.P. standards for the .223 Remington C.I.P. chambering.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] The Gw Pat 90 is used both in the Swiss military and in sports shooting.
[src:ammunition/5-56-45mm-nato-p02] Over 1 billion cartridges had been produced as of 2005.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The **.50 BMG** (**.50 Browning Machine Gun**), also known as **12.7×99mm NATO**, and designated as the **50 Browning** by the C.I.P., is a .50 in (12.7 mm) caliber cartridge developed for the M2 Browning heavy machine gun in the late 1910s, entering official service in 1921.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Under STANAG 4383, it is a standard service cartridge for NATO forces.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The cartridge itself has been made in many variants: multiple generations of regular ball, tracer, armor-piercing (AP), incendiary, and saboted sub-caliber penetrator rounds.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The rounds intended for machine guns are made into a continuous ammunition belt using metallic links.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The .50 BMG cartridge is also used in anti-materiel rifles.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A wide variety of ammunition is available, and the availability of match grade ammunition has increased the usefulness of .50 caliber rifles by allowing more accurate fire than lower-quality rounds.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] In response to the need for new anti-aircraft weaponry during World War I, John Browning developed the .50 BMG.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] He wanted the round to be used in a machine gun based on a scaled-up version of the M1917 Browning.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The development of the .50 BMG round is sometimes confused with the German 13.2 mm TuF, which Germany developed for an anti-tank rifle to combat British tanks during World War I and against aircraft.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The round was put into use in the M1921 Browning machine gun.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] During World War II, the .50 BMG was primarily used in the M2 Browning machine gun, in both its "light barrel" aircraft mount version and the "heavy barrel" (HB) version on ground vehicles, for anti-aircraft purposes.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] An upgraded variant of the M2 Browning HB machine gun used during World War II is still in use today.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Since the mid-1950s, some armored personnel carriers and utility vehicles have been designed to withstand 12.7 mm machine-gun fire, thereby limiting the destructive capability of the M2.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It still has more penetrating power than lighter weapons such as general-purpose machine guns, though it is significantly heavier and more cumbersome to transport.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Its range and accuracy, however, are superior to light machine guns when fixed on tripods.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It has not been replaced as the standard caliber for Western vehicle-mounted machine guns (Soviet and CIS armored vehicles mount 12.7×108mm NSVs, which have similar dimensions to .50 BMGs).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Decades later, the .50 BMG was chambered in high-powered rifles as well.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The Barrett M82 rifle was developed during the 1980s and, along with later variants, has upgraded the anti-materiel power of the military sniper.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The primary military use of this round is in the M2 Browning machine gun and anti-materiel rifles such as the Barrett M82.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Coast Guard uses .50 BMG rifles onboard armed helicopters to disable the engines on boats during interdictions.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Similarly, .50 BMG weapons have attracted attention from law enforcement agencies; they have been adopted by the New York City Police Department and the Pittsburgh Police.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A .50 BMG round can effectively disable a vehicle when fired into the engine block.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A .50 BMG round will penetrate most commercial brick walls and concrete cinder blocks.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The .50 BMG round was used as a sniper round as early as the Korean War.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Several world records for the longest confirmed kills were set with the .50 BMG.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Eventually, purpose-built sniper rifles were developed specifically for this round.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] In addition to long-range and anti-materiel, the U.S. military uses .50 BMG weapons to detonate unexploded ordnance from a safe distance.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It can disable most unarmored and lightly armored vehicles.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Some civilians use .50 caliber rifles for long-range target shooting: the US-based Fifty Caliber Shooters Association holds .50 BMG shooting matches.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The round is a scaled-up version of the .30-06 Springfield but uses a case wall with a long taper to facilitate feeding and extraction in various weapons.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 1 in 15 in (380 mm), with eight lands and grooves.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The primer type specified for this ammunition is a boxer primer with a single centralized ignition point (in the U.S. and NATO countries).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] However, some other countries produce the ammunition with Berdan primers that have two flash holes.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The average chamber pressure in this round as listed in TM43-0001-27, the U.S.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Army Ammunition Data Sheets — Small Caliber Ammunition, not including plastic practice, short cased spotter, or proof/test loads, is 54,923 psi (378,680 kPa).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The proof/test pressure is listed as 65,000 psi (450,000 kPa).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A common method for understanding the actual power of a cartridge is the comparison of muzzle energies.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The .30-06 Springfield, the standard caliber for American soldiers in both World Wars and a popular caliber amongst American hunters for medium to large game animals, can produce muzzle energies between 2,000 and 3,000 foot-pounds force (3,000 and 4,000 J).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The .50 BMG round can produce between 10,000 and 15,000 foot-pounds force (14,000 and 20,000 J), depending on its powder and bullet type, as well as the weapon it is fired from.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Due to the high ballistic coefficient of the bullet, the .50 BMG's trajectory also suffers less "drift" from crosswinds than smaller and lighter calibers, making the .50 BMG a good choice for high-powered sniper rifles.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This tracer is used for observing fire, signaling, target designation, and incendiary purposes.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge is used against unarmored, flammable targets.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The incendiary bullet has a light blue tip.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge is used against personnel and unarmored targets.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge is used against lightly armored vehicles, protective shelters, and personnel, and can be identified by its black tip.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge is used, in place of the armor-piercing round, against armored, flammable targets.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Tracer for observing fire, signaling, target designation, and incendiary purposes.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Designed to be less intense than the M1 tracer, the M10 has an orange tip.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge is used in place of the armor-piercing round against armored, flammable targets, with a tracer element for observation purposes.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It is effectively a variant of the M8 armor-piercing incendiary with the added tracer element.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Can be fired from the M82/M107 series of rifles.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This bullet has a red tip with a ring of aluminum paint.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Tracer for use in observing fire during air-to-air combat.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Designed to be more visible, the M21 is three times more brilliant than the M1 tracer.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The tip of the bullet is painted blue with a light blue ring.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge has a 355–360 gr (23.0–23.3 g) tungsten penetrator that is sabot-launched at a muzzle velocity of 4,000 feet per second (1,200 m/s).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The 0.50 in (12.7 mm) diameter sabot is designed to separate after leaving the muzzle, releasing the 0.30 in (7.62 mm) penetrator.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The sabot is injection-molded from a special high-strength plastic and reinforced with an aluminum insert in the base section.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The cartridge is identified by an amber sabot (Ultem 1000).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Used only in the M2 series of machine guns.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This round can penetrate 0.75 in (19 mm) of steel armor at 1,500 yards (1,400 m).
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Like the M903, this is a SLAP round, with the only difference being that the M962 also has a tracer element for observing fire, target designation, and incendiary purposes.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It has a red plastic sabot for identification and is used only in the M2 series of machine guns.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A long-range match cartridge specifically designed for long-range work using the M107 rifle.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The .50 caliber M1022 has an olive-green bullet coating with no tip ID coloration.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The projectile is of standard ball design.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It is designed for long-range sniper training and tactical use against targets that do not require armor-piercing or incendiary effects.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It exhibits superior long-range accuracy and is trajectory matched to MK211 grade A.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The M1022 is ideal for use in all .50 caliber bolt-action and semi-automatic sniper rifles.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Mod 0 HEIAP cartridge contains a .30 caliber tungsten penetrator, zirconium powder, and Composition A explosive.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A green tip with a gray ring identified the cartridge.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The .50 caliber Mk 257 API-DT has a purple bullet tip.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The bullet has a hardened-steel core and an incendiary tip.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Dim tracer reduces the possibility of the weapon being located during night fire and is visible only with night-vision devices.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The bullet has a hardened-steel core and features double valleys to reduce bearing surface, thereby decreasing friction and increasing stability.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] As per the Mk 211 Mod 0, but with a tracer component.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This cartridge is used against hardened targets such as bunkers, for suppressive fire against lightly armored vehicles, and ground and aerial threat suppression.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It is identified by a gray over yellow tip.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It has a clear polymer case with a standard brass head fused at the bottom.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The Mk 323 can be fired from M2HB/M2A1 machine guns and GAU-21/A aircraft guns with the same performance.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] It gives a 25 percent weight saving over brass-cased ammunition, allowing 40 percent more ammunition to be carried for the same weight.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The Mk 323's polymer casing is applied to tracer, AP, API, and SLAP projectiles.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency) contracted with Teledyne Scientific Company to develop the EXACTO program, including a .50-caliber guided bullet.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Videos published by DARPA show the guided bullet diverting to strike a moving target.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Three distinct and non-compatible metallic links have been used for the .50 BMG cartridge belts.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The M2 and M9 links, "pull-out" designs, are used in the Browning M2 and M3 machine guns.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The M15-series metal "push-through" links were used in the M85 machine gun.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Pull-out cloth belts were also used at one time, but have been obsolete since 1945.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Within the United Kingdom, it is legal to own a bolt-action .50 BMG rifle with a section 1 Firearms Certificate.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Applications requesting firearms in this caliber are assessed by the same criteria as smaller calibers, with the applicant having to prove they have a valid reason for owning such a weapon.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The specified maximum diameter of an unfired .50 BMG bullet is 0.510 inches (13.0 mm); while this appears to be over the .50 inch (12.7 mm) maximum allowed for non-sporting Title I firearms under the U.S.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] National Firearms Act, the barrel of a .50 BMG rifle is only .50 inch (12.7 mm) across the rifling lands and slightly larger in the grooves.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] The oversized bullet is formed to the bore size upon firing, forming a tight seal and engaging the rifling.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Despite political controversy over the cartridge's great power (it is the most powerful commonly available cartridge not considered a destructive device under the National Firearms Act), it remains popular among long-range shooters for its accuracy and external ballistics.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] While the .50 BMG round can deliver accurate shot placement (if match grade ammunition is used) at ranges over 1,000-yard (910 m), smaller-caliber rifles produce better scores and tighter groups in 1,000-yard (910 m) competitions.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] A 1999 Justice Department Office of Special Investigations briefing on .50 caliber rifle crime identified several instances of the .50 BMG being involved in criminal activities.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] None of the cited cases has confirmed domestic violent criminal use of a .50 BMG firearm, and a majority of the domestic cases were possession charges.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] In the United States, Washington, D.C. disallows registration of .50 BMG rifles, thus rendering civilian possession unlawful.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] California prohibits the private purchase of a rifle capable of firing the .50 BMG through the .50 Caliber BMG Regulation Act of 2004.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Connecticut specifically bans the Barrett 82A1 .50 BMG rifle.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] However, .50 BMG rifles registered before the enacted bans remain lawful to possess in California and Connecticut.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] In Illinois, it is legal to possess a .50 caliber rifle only if it was acquired by January 10, 2023, and it was registered with the state police by January 1, 2024.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Maryland imposes additional regulations on the sale and transfer of .50 BMG rifles and other weapons classed as "regulated firearms", and limits purchases of any firearm within this class to one per month, but does not impose registration requirements or any form of categorical ban.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] Contrary to a persistent misconception within the United States Armed Forces, using .50 BMG directly against enemy personnel is not prohibited by the laws of war.
[src:ammunition/50-bmg] This limitation was entirely tactical and intended to hide the vulnerable M40 and its crew from the enemy until the main anti-tank gun was ready to fire; however, Parks concludes that some U.S. troops assumed the existence of a legal limitation on the use of .50-caliber projectiles more generally.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] An **aerial bomb** is a type of explosive or incendiary weapon intended to travel through the air on a predictable trajectory.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Engineers usually develop such bombs to be dropped from an aircraft.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The use of aerial bombs is termed **aerial bombing**.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Aerial bombs include a vast range and complexity of designs.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] These include unguided gravity bombs, guided bombs, bombs hand-tossed from a vehicle, bombs needing a large specially-built delivery-vehicle, bombs integrated with the vehicle itself (such as a glide bomb), instant-detonation bombs, or delay-action bombs.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] As with other types of explosive weapons, aerial bombs aim to kill and injure people or to destroy materiel through the projection of one or more of blast, fragmentation, radiation or fire outwards from the point of detonation.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The first bombs delivered to their targets by air were single bombs carried on unmanned hot air balloons, launched by the Austrians against Venice in 1849 during the First Italian War of Independence.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The first bombs dropped from a heavier-than-air aircraft were grenades or grenade-like devices.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Historically, the first use was by Giulio Gavotti on 1 November 1911, during the Italo-Turkish War.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] In 1912, during the First Balkan War, Bulgarian Air Force pilot Hristo Toprakchiev suggested the use of aircraft to drop "bombs" (called grenades in the Bulgarian army at this time) on Turkish positions.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Captain Simeon Petrov developed the idea and created several prototypes by adapting different types of grenades and increasing their payload.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] On 16 October 1912, observer Prodan Tarakchiev dropped two of those bombs on the Turkish railway station of Karaağaç (near the besieged Edirne) from an Albatros F.2 aircraft piloted by Radul Milkov, for the first time in this campaign.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] During the Mexican Revolution, US inventor Lester P.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Barlow convinced General Pancho Villa of the insurgent Villista forces to purchase a plane from which bombs were dropped on trains carrying on Mexican Federal troops.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Although the bombs were weak, they launched Barlow's career as an explosives inventor.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Aerial bombing saw widespread use during World War Two.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] A precursor was the 1937 bombing of Guernica by the Nazi German Luftwaffe and the Fascist Italian Aviazione Legionaria at the behest of Francisco Franco.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The bombs used were a mix of high-explosive bombs and 1 kg (2.2 lb) incendiaries, that Germany would later use also against the UK.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] As part of the Blitz, Nazi-Germany's Coventry Blitz set a benchmark for destruction that caused Joseph Goebbels to later use the term *coventriert* ("coventried") to describe similar levels of destruction of enemy cities.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] While a single raid of the Coventry Blitz killed almost 600 people, later allied raids using conventional aerial bombs each killed up to tens of thousands of people, with the bombing of Dresden and the bombing of Hamburg as notable examples.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The final stages of World War Two saw the most lethal air raid in history, the bombing of Tokyo where possibly 100,000 or more were killed primarily by incendiary bombs.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The majority of these incendiary bombs were the 500-pound (230 kg) E-46 cluster bomb which released 38 M-69 oil-based incendiary bombs at an altitude of 2,500 ft (760 m).
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] The end of World War Two was brought about with the aerial, atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki that killed between 150,000 and 246,000 people and which remain the only use of nuclear weapons in an armed conflict.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] An example of extensive use of aerial bombs after World War Two is the U.S. aerial bombing during the Vietnam War, where the amount of bombs dropped was more than three times what the USA dropped during World War II in Europe and Asia.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Aerial bombs typically use a contact fuze to detonate the bomb upon impact, or a delayed-action fuze initiated by impact.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Not all bombs dropped detonate; failures are common.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] It was estimated that during the Second World War about 10% of German bombs failed to detonate, and that Allied bombs had a failure rate of 15% or 20%, especially if they hit soft soil and used a pistol-type detonating mechanism rather than fuzes.
[src:ammunition/aerial-bomb] Old bombs occasionally detonate when disturbed, or when a faulty time fuze eventually functions, showing that precautions are still essential when dealing with them.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Ammunition categories are used to define firearm ammunition types considered safe for transport.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] The UN Division system and UN Number system categorizes any explosive material by the speed of burning and amount of explosive.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] The United Nations has also instituted a categorisation system specifically for handgun ammunition.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Both these systems can be used together to define safe amounts of ammunition that can be carried on various modes of transport, including civilian scheduled flights.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] 1.4S, UN 0012 or UN 0014** denotes the categories of ammunition that the IATA permits to be carried on passenger flights.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] In simple terms, each passenger may carry up to 5 kg of weapons cartridges of less than 19.1 mm caliber being either blanks or with solid projectiles, in their checked baggage.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Local gun laws may deviate from IATA rules by prohibiting it with some types of weapons or having special rules for transport that sometimes conflict with IATA regulations.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Airlines may also have their own rules and procedures that sometimes conflict with each other, with IATA rules or even local laws and regulations.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] For example, some jurisdictions require the firearm and ammunition to be transported in separate cases, while other jurisdictions require them to be transported in the same case.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] This may, depending on jurisdiction, be solved by using two or more separate cases fitted inside a common larger case.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Some jurisdictions even require integral parts of the firearm to be disassembled and put into two separate cases, while others require the firearm to be complete.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Travelers are therefore encouraged to check all relevant regulations depending on where they travel, both in regards to the departure, destination and any stopovers.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Firearm cartridges in general are regarded as being constructed such that they pose little danger during fires.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] If ignited by intense heat the cartridge will burst, but the particles will typically not travel very far, and protective firefighter clothing is generally considered sufficient to stop the fragments.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] However, if cartridges are stored in an airtight metal chamber, dangerous pressures may occur during a fire.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] For this reason, it is generally recommended to transport ammunition in original boxes sold by the manufacturer or plastic boxes intended for safe transport.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] Most types of civilian firearms ammunition is classified as division 1.4S.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] The division 1.4 in the UN explosives shipping classification system covers cargo with minor explosion hazard, while the suffix "S" refers to the packaging being made so as to not hinder nearby firefighters.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] The United Nations has categorised all forms of dangerous goods, and the categories regarding explosive materials are listed at List of UN numbers#UN 0001 to 1000.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] The most relevant UN numbers for civilian ammunition transport is UN 0012 and UN 0014.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] UN 0012 defines the category 'Cartridges for weapons, inert projectile or Cartridges, small arms', being "Ammunition consisting of a cartridge case fitted with a centre or rimfire primer and containing both a propelling charge and solid projectiles.
[src:ammunition/air-travel-with-firearms-and-ammunition] They are designed to be fired in weapons of calibre not larger than 19.1 mm.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] Some aircraft types can carry a wide variety of ordnance – for example, the Fairchild AU-23 Peacemaker could use forward-firing gun pods, 500 and 250 pound bombs, napalm units, cluster bomb units, flares, rockets, smoke grenades and propaganda leaflet dispensers.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] For many weapons there is a limit to the length of time they can be flown (e.g. because of vibration damage); after this their safety or effectiveness is not guaranteed.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] This can be a problem if weapons designed for high intensity conflict are carried on multiple missions in a long counter-insurgency campaign.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] The first recorded use of aircraft ordinance during a conflict was during the Italo-Turkish War in 1911.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] The Italian Army Air Corps Blériot XI and Nieuport IV used monoplanes to bomb a Turkish camp at Ain Zara in Libya.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] The First World War which followed shortly after saw rapid development for aircraft and their corresponding ordinance.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] Ordnance can be divided into **guided** and **unguided** categories based on their targeting capabilities.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] **Guided ordnance**, such as precision-guided munitions *(PGMs)*, use advanced technologies like GPS, infrared, radar or laser tracking to precisely hit designated targets.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] **Unguided ordnance**, commonly known as "dumb bombs," lack guidance systems and rely on the aircraft’s release parameters to strike a target.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] Though less accurate, unguided bombs are often used for area strikes and are more cost-effective.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] Air-to-air ordnance is a weapon fired from an aircraft to strike air targets, such as the Chinese PL series AAMs (PL-2, PL-5, PL-8, PL-9, PL-10, PL-11, PL-12, PL-15, PL-17, PL-21) or the French MICA series AAMs.
[src:ammunition/aircraft-ordnance] There are several kinds of air-to-air missiles, most commonly identified using the "fox" (short for "foxtrot" identification system.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:ammunition/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] An **ammunition box** or **cartridge box** is a container designed for safe transport and storage of ammunition.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] It is typically made of metal, wood, and corrugated fiberboard, etc.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Boxes are labelled with caliber, quantity, and manufacturing date, lot number, UN dangerous goods labels.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] With a metal container, rubber gasket is commonly found in the hinged lid to protect the ammunition from moisture damage.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] With other containers, plastic bags and desiccants can be used.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] The resealing ammunition box is largely a NATO tradition.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Warsaw Pact nations typically stored and transported ammunition in single-use "spam cans".
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] They had crates that had a sealed zinc lining on the inside.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Some enthusiasts and investors collect historical ammunition boxes.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Many also use them as containers for the recreational activity of Geocaching.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Due to their durable construction, used metal ammunition boxes are popularly re-used for general storage and other purposes.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] They are a popular choice for geocaching containers.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Used ammunition boxes have lead and propellant residue inside, so they should not be used to store food or drink.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Commercially-made new or fully reconditioned used boxes do not have this problem.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Used boxes are often sold at military surplus stores.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Shipments of explosives and similar hazards are highly regulated.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] Based on the UN Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods model regulations, each country has coordinated design and performance requirements for shipment.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] For example, in the US, the Department of Transportation has jurisdiction and published requirements in Title 49 of the Code of Federal Regulations.
[src:ammunition/ammunition-box] The applicable regulation depends on the level of hazard, quantity being shipped, mode of transit, etc.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:ammunition/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:ammunition/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:ammunition/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
